      <sec id="article-30540.s9" sec-type="Complications">
        <title>Complications</title>
        <p>The complication rate of traumatic mediastinal injuries is difficult to determine as the majority of these injuries occur concurrently with other injuries. Complications that occur in these patients can include bronchial or esophageal stricture.&#x000a0;In addition, patients with tracheal or esophageal injury can develop tracheoesophageal fistulas. Patients with mediastinal trauma can develop empyema or ventilator-associated pneumonia.&#x000a0;In addition, thoracic duct injury and chylothorax can also occur.</p>
      </sec>
      <sec id="article-30540.s10" sec-type="Pearls and Other Issues">
        <title>Pearls and Other Issues</title>
        <list list-type="bullet">
          <list-item>
            <p>Patients with mediastinal trauma should be evaluated using ATLS protocol.</p>
          </list-item>
          <list-item>
            <p>Endoscopy and bronchoscopy can help identify mediastinal injuries and plan the surgical approach.</p>
          </list-item>
          <list-item>
            <p>Patients with blunt mediastinal injury will often have multiple injuries.</p>
          </list-item>
          <list-item>
            <p>Patients with penetrating mediastinal trauma have the highest survival rate among all patients undergoing resuscitative thoracotomy.</p>
          </list-item>
        </list>
      </sec>
      <sec id="article-30540.s11" sec-type="Enhancing Healthcare Team Outcomes ">
        <title>Enhancing Healthcare Team Outcomes </title>
        <p>Mediastinal trauma is best managed by an interprofessional team that includes an anesthesiologist, thoracic surgeon, cardiac surgeon, trauma specialist, intensivist and ICU nurses. It is important to assess all organs of the mediastinum for injury with imaging studies. No healthcare worker should perform an emergency room thoracotomy without having knowledge of anatomy and/or prior surgical experience-otherwise the mortality rates are close to 100%.</p>
        <p>The outcomes for patients with mediastinal injury depend on the age of patient, severity of injury, number of organs involved, associated head trauma and presence of hypotension on arrival.</p>
      </sec>
